The '''Colored Female Religious and Moral Society''' was an [[African Americans|African American]] [[Woman's club movement|women's club]] organized in 1818 in [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Scott|first=Anne Firor|date=1990-01-01|year=|title=Most Invisible of All: Black Women's Voluntary Associations|jstor=2210662|journal=The Journal of Southern History|volume=56|issue=1|pages=6|doi=10.2307/2210662|registration=y}}</ref> The group was started by forty women and they created their own [[constitution]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EzGVKN0BHFQC&lpg=PA108&ots=QnNSQkmRjw&dq=%22Colored%20Female%20Religious%20and%20Moral%20Society%22&pg=PA108#v=onepage&q=%22Colored%20Female%20Religious%20and%20Moral%20Society%22&f=false|title=We are Your Sisters: Black Women in the Nineteenth Century|last=Sterling|first=Dorothy|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=1997|isbn=9780393316292|edition=Revised|location=|pages=108|quote=|via=}}</ref> The group's constitution was published in the ''[[The Liberator (anti-slavery newspaper)|Liberator]]'', an abolitionist paper.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2Bh8CwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA269&ots=m2cFIhaKTx&dq=%22Colored%20Female%20Religious%20and%20Moral%20Society%22&pg=PA269#v=onepage&q=%22Colored%20Female%20Religious%20and%20Moral%20Society%22&f=false|title=The Slave's Cause: A History of Abolition|last=Sinha|first=Manisha|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2016|isbn=9780300182088|location=|pages=269|quote=|via=}}</ref> The members promised that they would "be charitably watchful over each other."<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d9lhBw8t410C&lpg=PA62&ots=LyTRfAHXfS&dq=%22Colored%20Female%20Religious%20and%20Moral%20Society%22&pg=PA62#v=onepage&q=%22Colored%20Female%20Religious%20and%20Moral%20Society%22&f=false|title=The Reader's Companion to U.S. Women's History|last=Shaw|first=Stephanie J.|publisher=Mariner Books|year=1999|isbn=9780618001828|editor-last=Mankiller|editor-first=Wilma P.|edition=Reprint|location=|pages=62|chapter=Black Clubwomen's Movement|quote=|editor-last2=Mink|editor-first2=Gwendolyn|editor-last3=Navarro|editor-first3=Marysa|editor-last4=Smith|editor-first4=Barbara|editor-last5=Steinem|editor-first5=Gloria|via=}}</ref> Members also were required to take an [[oath]] of secrecy.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w_b9ih_U8NAC&lpg=PT193&ots=pys7arbUX1&dq=%22Colored%20Female%20Religious%20and%20Moral%20Society%22&pg=PT193#v=onepage&q=%22Colored%20Female%20Religious%20and%20Moral%20Society%22&f=false|title=Love of Freedom: Black Women in Colonial and Revolutionary New England|last=Adams|first=Catherine|last2=Pleck|first2=Elizabeth H.|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2010|isbn=9780199779833|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> The organization was religious in nature, but they also worked to get sickness and death benefits for others.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1NNRCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA149&ots=vxoN1GUfgd&dq=%22Colored%20Female%20Religious%20and%20Moral%20Society%22&pg=PA149#v=onepage&q=%22Colored%20Female%20Religious%20and%20Moral%20Society%22&f=false|title=Religion in America|last=Corrigan|first=John|last2=Hudson|first2=Winthrop|publisher=Routledge|year=2016|isbn=9781317344605|edition=8th|location=|pages=149|quote=|via=}}</ref> In 1833, after membership had dwindled, the society was again revived.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://theliberatorfiles.com/colored-female-society-in-salem/|title=Colored Female Society in Salem|last=|first=|date=16 February 1833|newspaper=The Liberator|access-date=8 February 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|work=|via=The Liberator Files}}</ref> Many of the members were "[[Christian]] propertied elite."<ref name=":0" />
